Classification Modeling on Online Shoppers Intention Dataset¶

In this document, we will impleament 8 different ML algorithms on the a dataset from UCI ML Repo. This dataset contains information on people's purchase decision as a column Revenue consisting of two categories – True and False. We are interested in building a classifier for people's purchase decision given all other factors such as thier region, time (month, whether it's on weekend, whether it's near a holiday), product browsing history (number and duration of related item viewed, website bounce rate, exit rate), etc.

The total 12330 entries in this data belongs to all different users (i.e. independent). The dataset was formed so that each session would belong to a different user in a 1-year period to avoid any tendency to a specific campaign, special day, user profile, or period.

The "Special Day" feature indicates the closeness of the site visiting time to a specific special day (e.g. Mother’s Day, Valentine's Day) in which the sessions are more likely to be finalized with transaction. The value of this attribute is determined by considering the dynamics of e-commerce such as the duration between the order date and delivery date. For example, for Valentina’s day, this value takes a nonzero value between February 2 and February 12, zero before and after this date unless it is close to another special day, and its maximum value of 1 on February 8.

def AvgMinutes(Count, Duration):
    if Duration == 0:
        output = 0
    elif Duration != 0:
        output = float(Duration)/float(Count)
    return output
    
Columns = [['Administrative', 'Administrative_Duration'], ['Informational', 'Informational_Duration'], ['ProductRelated', 'ProductRelated_Duration']]
    
    
X['AvgAdministrative'] = X.apply(lambda x: AvgMinutes(Count = x['Administrative'], Duration = x['Administrative_Duration']), axis = 1)
X['AvgInformational'] = X.apply(lambda x: AvgMinutes(Count = x['Informational'], Duration = x['Informational_Duration']), axis = 1)
X['AvgProductRelated'] = X.apply(lambda x: AvgMinutes(Count = x['ProductRelated'], Duration = x['ProductRelated_Duration']), axis = 1)
X.drop(['Administrative', 'Administrative_Duration','Informational', 'Informational_Duration','ProductRelated', 'ProductRelated_Duration'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

from sklearn import linear_model

params_LM = {
    "loss" : ["hinge", "log", "squared_hinge", "modified_huber"],
    "alpha" : [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1],
    "penalty" : ["l2", "l1", "none"],
}
In [ ]:
'''
time_spend_LM = {}
time_spend_finetuned_LM = {}
accuracy_LM = {}            # ACCURACY = (TP + TN)/(TP + TN + FP + FN)
confusion_matrix_LM = {}
f1_score_LM = {}            # F1 = 2 * (PRECISION * RECALL)/(PRECISION + RECALL)`
recall_LM = {}              # RECALL = TP/(TP + FN)
precision_LM = {}           # PRECISION = TP/(TP + FP)
roc_auc_score_LM = {}

for i in split:
  X = X_train.iloc[:i, :]
  y = y_train.iloc[:i]

  time0 = time.perf_counter()
  model = linear_model.SGDClassifier(random_state = 99, max_iter = 10000)
  model.fit(X, y) 
  time1 = time.perf_counter()
  time_spend_LM[i] = time1 - time0

  time0 = time.perf_counter()
  model = linear_model.SGDClassifier(max_iter=10000)
  model = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=params_LM).fit(X,y)
  time1 = time.perf_counter()
  time_spend_finetuned_LM[i] = time1 - time0

  filename = 'lm_SGDClassifier_{size}.pkl'.format(size = i)
  pickle.dump(model, open(filename, 'wb'))

  y_pred_LM = model.predict(X_test)

  acc_LM = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_LM) 
  cm_LM = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_LM)
  f1_LM = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
  rec_LM = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
  prec_LM = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
  roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)

  accuracy_LM[i] = acc_LM  
  confusion_matrix_LM[i] = cm_LM
  f1_score_LM[i] = f1_LM
  recall_LM[i] = rec_LM
  precision_LM[i] = prec_LM
  roc_auc_score_LM[i] = roc_auc

rep = 10
num_dataset = len(split)

time_spend_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep, num_dataset)), columns = split)
accuracy_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep,num_dataset)), columns = split)
recall_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep,num_dataset)), columns = split)
confusion_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep,num_dataset)), columns = split)
precision_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep,num_dataset)), columns = split)
roc_auc_matrix = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros((rep, num_dataset)), columns = split)

avg_time_spend = {}
avg_acc = {}
avg_recall = {}
avg_precision = {}
avg_roc_auc = {}

  j = total_len
  %cd /content/drive/My Drive/AutoML /LM/model/all
  
  data = pd.concat([X_train, y_train], axis=1)
  data = data.sample(frac = 1)
  X = data.iloc[:j,:].drop('Class', axis = 1)
  y = data.iloc[:j]['Class']

  for i in range(rep):
      time0 = time.perf_counter()
      model = linear_model.SGDClassifier()
      model = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=params_LM,cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2).fit(X,y)
      time1 = time.perf_counter()
      time_spend = time1-time0

      filename = 'lm_SGDClassifier_{size}_{iter}.pkl'.format(size = j, iter = i+1)
      pickle.dump(model, open(filename, 'wb'))

      y_pred_LM = model.predict(X_test)

      accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_LM) 
      print('iter:{}, sample:{}, acc:{}'.format(i+1, j, accuracy))
      tpr = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
      precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
      roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)

      time_spend_matrix.loc[i,j] = time_spend
      accuracy_matrix.loc[i,j] = accuracy
      recall_matrix.loc[i,j] = tpr
      precision_matrix.loc[i,j] = precision
      roc_auc_matrix.loc[i,j] = roc_auc

  avg_time_spend[j] = time_spend_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()
  avg_acc[j] = accuracy_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()
  avg_recall[j] = recall_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()
  avg_precision[j] = precision_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()
  avg_roc_auc[j] = roc_auc_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()

avg_f1 = {}
avg_recall = {}
avg_precision = {}

  %cd f'/content/drive/My Drive/AutoML /LM/model/{j}'
  data = pd.concat([X_train, y_train], axis=1)
  data = data.sample(frac = 1)
  X = data.iloc[:j,:].drop('Class', axis = 1)
  y = data.iloc[:j]['Class']

  for i in range(rep):
      time0 = time.perf_counter()
      model = linear_model.SGDClassifier(max_iter=500000)
      model = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid=params_LM).fit(X,y)
      time1 = time.perf_counter()
      time_spend = time1-time0

      filename = 'lm_SGDClassifier_{size}_{iter}.pkl'.format(size = j,iter = i+1)
      pickle.dump(model, open(filename, 'wb'))

      y_pred_LM = model.predict(X_test)

      accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_LM) 
      print('iter:{}, sample:{}, acc:{}'.format(i+1, j, accuracy))
      tpr = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
      precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)
      roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_LM)

      time_spend_matrix.loc[i,j] = time_spend
      accuracy_matrix.loc[i,j] = accuracy
      recall_matrix.loc[i,j] = tpr
      precision_matrix.loc[i,j] = precision
      roc_auc_matrix.loc[i,j] = roc_auc

  avg_time_spend[j] = time_spend_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()

  avg_recall[j] = recall_matrix.loc[:,j].mean()

Visualizing model performance¶

In [ ]:
def plot_time(dict, model_name):
  size = list(dict.keys())
  time = list(dict.values())
  plt.plot(size, time)
  plt.xlabel('training sample size')
  plt.ylabel('time used in training (in fractional seconds)')
  plt.title('The times spent training the {model} with varying training data size'.format(model = model_name))


def plot_model_performance(dict, model_name, performance_score):
  size = list(dict.keys())           
  acc = list(dict.values())
  plt.plot(size, acc)
  plt.xlabel('training sample size')
  plt.ylabel('{}'.format(performance_score))
  plt.ylim(0, 1)
  plt.title('The {model} {performance} with varying training data size'.format(
      model = model_name, performance = performance_score))
In [ ]:
plot_time(avg_time_spend, 'linear model')
In [ ]:
plot_model_performance(avg_acc, 'linear model', 'accuracy')

F1 Score is the weighted average of Precision and Recall. Therefore, this score takes both false positives and false negatives into account. Intuitively it is not as easy to understand as accuracy, but F1 is usually more useful than accuracy, especially if you have an uneven class distribution. It is the harmonic mean(average) of the precision and recall. F1 Score is best if there is some sort of balance between precision (p) & recall (r) in the system. Oppositely F1 Score isn't so high if one measure is improved at the expense of the other.

When to use to decision tree:

  1. When you want your model to be simple and explainable
  2. When you want non parametric model
  3. When you don't want to worry about feature selection or regularization or worry about multi-collinearity.
  4. You can overfit the tree and build a model if you are sure of validation or test data set is going to be subset of training data set or almost overlapping instead of unexpected.

When to use random forest :

  1. When you don't bother much about interpreting the model but want better accuracy.
  2. Random forest will reduce variance part of error rather than bias part, so on a given training data set decision tree may be more accurate than a random forest. But on an unexpected validation data set, Random forest always wins in terms of accuracy.

      tpr = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_AdaBoost)
      precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_AdaBoost)
      roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_AdaBoost)

      time_spend_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[i,j] = time_spend
      accuracy_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[i,j] = accuracy
      recall_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[i,j] = tpr
      precision_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[i,j] = precision
      roc_auc_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[i,j] = roc_auc

    avg_time_spend_AdaBoost[j] = time_spend_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[:,j].mean()
    avg_acc_AdaBoost[j] = accuracy_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[:,j].mean()
    avg_recall_AdaBoost[j] = recall_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[:,j].mean()
    avg_precision_AdaBoost[j] = precision_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[:,j].mean()
    avg_roc_auc_AdaBoost[j] = roc_auc_matrix_AdaBoost.loc[:,j].mean()
